abor in a Globalizing City: Prospects for Coalition Building in Nashville / rCornfield, Daniel B. / Canak, William -- t10. Building an Inclusive City: Labor-Community Coalitions and the Struggle for Urban Power in San Jose / rRhee, Nari / Sadler, Julie Anna -- tPart IV. INTERNATIONAL COMPARISONS -- t11. Special Interests and Public Goods: Organized Labor's Coalition Politics in Hamburg and Seattle / rGreer, Ian -- t12. Organizing Labor in London: Lessons from the Campaign for a Living Wage / rHolgate, Jane / Wills, Jane -- t13. Restructuring without Unions: The Polycentric Region of Greater Frankfurt / rJacobi, Otto -- tConclusion. Seeking Solidarity ... Why, and with Whom? / rCornfield, Daniel B. -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLabor in the New Urban Battlegrounds examines a diverse array of innovative strategies for revitalizing the labor movement by forming alliances outside the workplace with a variety of community groups, social movements, and faith-based organizations, particularly those that address civil rights, immigrant rights, and consumer concerns. This book presents case studies of issues-such as living wages, community development corporations, and local politics-around which urban coalitions are built in "union towns" (New York City, Boston, Buffalo, and Seattle), "frontier cities" (Los Angeles, Miami, San Jose, and Nashville), and European cities (London, Frankfurt, and Hamburg).Introducing the role of urban social context in the field of labor revitalization, the editors have chosen cases with different outcomes-cities in which strong coalitions have enabled new union influence are contrasted with those in which such coalition building has been thwarted. As they survey the successes and failures of the new urban labor movement, the editors and contributors conclude that actor choice, strategic innovation, coalition building, and the urban context of labor organizing are key elements in the revitalization of the labor movement and the renewal of democracy. This book will allow the labor leaders of the future to learn from the recent experiences of their peers throughout the United States and Europe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 20. Sep 2019) 0aCommunity development, UrbanzUnited States. 0aLabor movementzUnited States. 0aLabor unionszUnited States. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aCornfield, Daniel B., eeditor.1 aEvans, Peter B.1 aTurner, Lowell, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066750908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501726682423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501726682.jpg  a978-3-11-063872-1  DG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-066750-9  COR eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA15STM  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA3STM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG